</P>
<P>
Randall Terry, founder of the anti-abortion group Operation Rescue, said he
and other conservatives would continue lobbying Congress and the Florida
Legislature to pass bills that could prolong Schiavo's life. In
particular, he said, they would urge the House of Representatives
to take up a bill passed by the Senate Thursday,
which would set up a federal court hearing in cases
like Schiavo's to evaluate whether the state had followed all
requirements for judicial due process.
</P>
<P>
"We will hold the House leadership accountable if this thing fails,"
said Terry, who acted as a spokesman for the Schindlers
outside the hospice Friday. "The conservative right of this country
has labored fiercely for two decades to finally get control
of both houses. We didn't get here so they could
pour this down the drain."
</P>
<P>
After Schiavo's feeding tube was removed, Republican leaders of Congress expressed
strong disappointment and pledged to work through the weekend to
try to strike an agreement on legislation that could shift
the case into federal court.
</P>
<P>
"Right now, murder is being committed against a defenseless American citizen
in Florida," DeLay said. "Terri Schiavo's feeding tube should be
immediately replaced, and Congress will continue working to explore ways
to save her."
</P>
<P>
Congressional Democrats, meanwhile, steered clear of the issue for the most
part, though some continued to wonder if Congress should be
so deeply involved.
</P>
<P>
"I intend to do all I can to see that any
action Congress takes is constructive and free from partisan politics,
and does not make a tragic situation worse by exploiting
this terrible tragedy," said Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts,
the senior Democrat on the health committee.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with reporters, DeLay, joined by other senior Republicans,
again insisted that the best way to resolve the deadlock
was for the Senate to on Monday approve a much
broader House-passed measure that would apply new federal legal protection
in all such cases.
</P>
<P>
But Senate officials were pessimistic they could force the House bill
through since it had drawn strong objections from members of
both parties previously.
</P>
<P>
DeLay and Rep. Roy Blunt of Missouri, the majority whip, said
their viewing of videotape of Schiavo convinced them she wanted
to live and they were not persuaded by her husband's
claim that she would prefer to be allowed to die.
</P>
<P>
"I think the sanctity of life overshadows the sanctity of marriage,"
said DeLay.
</P>
